# ADR-0017 — Everything Is a Capability

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

As the platform evolves, new functionality is continuously introduced.

Examples include:

- Runtime Tools
- AI Agents
- Knowledge Providers
- Memory Providers
- Execution Strategies
- Plugins
- Integrations

If each subsystem introduces its own registration,
discovery and loading mechanism, the platform gradually becomes fragmented.

Different modules would expose different extension models,
making the system difficult to evolve.

A single architectural abstraction is required.

---

# Decision

Everything that extends the platform shall be represented as a Capability.

A Capability is the universal extension unit of the Pharos AI Operating
System.

Examples include:

- Agent Capabilities
- Tool Capabilities
- Memory Capabilities
- Knowledge Capabilities
- Runtime Capabilities
- Plugin Capabilities

Capabilities become the common language of the platform.

---

# Capability

A Capability describes **what** can be done.

It never describes **who** performs it.

Examples:

```
software.architecture.design
```

```
flutter.analysis
```

```
filesystem.read
```

```
knowledge.retrieve
```

```
memory.search
```

```
calendar.create_event
```

Capabilities are stable identifiers.

Implementations may change.

---

# Capability Providers

Different components provide capabilities.

Examples:

```
EngineeringAgent

↓

software.architecture.design
```

```
FileTool

↓

filesystem.read
```

```
MarkdownKnowledgeProvider

↓

knowledge.retrieve
```

```
VectorMemoryProvider

↓

memory.semantic_search
```

The platform reasons about capabilities rather than concrete classes.

---

# Discovery

Capabilities are registered at startup.

Consumers never instantiate implementations directly.

Instead they request capabilities.

```
Coordinator

↓

Capability Registry

↓

Capability Provider
```

The same discovery mechanism applies across the platform.

---

# Runtime

Runtime remains capability-agnostic.

Runtime executes RuntimeIntent.

Runtime never performs capability discovery.

Capability resolution belongs to the Intelligence Layer.

---

# Architectural Principles

## Behaviour over Identity

The system asks:

"What capability is required?"

rather than

"Which class should I instantiate?"

---

## Open for Extension

New functionality is introduced through new capabilities.

Existing orchestration logic remains unchanged.

---

## Replaceable Implementations

A capability may have multiple implementations.

Example:

```
filesystem.read

↓

Local File Tool
```

or

```
filesystem.read

↓

Remote Storage Tool
```

The consumer remains unchanged.

---

## Unified Extension Model

All extension mechanisms follow one architectural concept.

The platform avoids separate registries for:

- tools
- agents
- plugins
- providers

---

# Dependency Rules

Capability consumers never depend on concrete implementations.

Capability providers never depend on consumers.

Registries expose contracts only.

Runtime never resolves capabilities directly.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Separate registry per subsystem

Rejected.

Leads to duplicated infrastructure and inconsistent extension models.

---

## Instantiate implementations directly

Rejected.

Violates Dependency Inversion and limits extensibility.

---

## Agent-specific capabilities only

Rejected.

Capabilities should be a platform-wide concept.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- one extension model
- consistent architecture
- easier plugin development
- scalable discovery
- reusable infrastructure

Negative:

- additional abstraction
- requires capability governance

The consistency benefits outweigh the additional abstraction.

---

# Future Evolution

Capabilities may later support:

- versioning
- priorities
- permissions
- dependency graphs
- semantic matching
- remote discovery
- marketplace distribution

The architectural model remains unchanged.

